First I find the other box where my choice makes a difference and I start from there. I evaluate all the boxes and predict which choice the person will pick. With that in mind I look at if the next person knew what that person was going to pick  which one would the next person pick  and then the next person so on and so fourth. looked at what was best for me and the other person

When playing the game  I figured out that if I could predict what the other player would choose  I would make my decision based on that prediction. Also  I noticed that there was always one player whose X row contained higher numbers than their Y row or vice-versa. Therefore  based on the obvious choice that that player would make  I would be able to predict the choices of other players. This strategy only failed me once after I figured out how to do it. I figured it was not about getting the highest number in my panel  but getting the highest number based on my predictions of what each of the other players was going to choose.

Figure out which player had a definite best option and what it would be then figure out how consequently the next person would act based on that optimal option and apply their decision to the next and so forth.

I would try to geuss what everyone else was going to choose by looking at everyones options. Its a chain reaction of effects. Sometimes you only had to look at one persons options  other times you had to see them all.

If one chose was advantageous regardless of what another player chose  I went with that answer. If the answer was unclear and more up to chance  I saw what the player who chose how much I was paid would rationally choose based off of her payoff choices.

I would look at the color who my pay off depended on. I expected that person to choose the most amount for them. If it is indeterminable  I would look at the color before them  and see their best choice to make the most money. Then I would make my choice depending on what the best option would be for others.

I looked at the highest number on my table and chose the action that corresponded to it.  If I made  that choice  I would look to see what the best choice would be for the person affected by my actions.  I would then look at the best choice for the person affected by their actions.  I would then find the best choice for the person affected by their action.  This final action I would then use to determine my action  which ended up most often being the second highest number in my table.

At least one color will always have an obvious better option (both numbers for X are higher than Y). That player will always choose that better option  and so all other players will choose either X or Y according to their higher payoff to follow suit.

I would look back at the other players in the game and try to understand what their dominant strategy was. With that knowledge I would try to infer what they were going to pick  and choose a response that would maximize my earnings based on what I thought they would select.
